## Architecture Decision — One-Shot Map Generation

### Decision Made

Switch from **click-to-expand** architecture to **one-shot architecture**.

### Current Architecture (click-to-expand)

- User enters query → center node appears
- User clicks node → new AI call made
- Each expansion is isolated, AI has no context of other nodes
- 5 clicks = 5 separate API calls = 3,100 tokens per session
- Nodes can contradict or overlap each other
- Incoherent map structure

### New Architecture (one-shot)

- User enters query → one AI call generates entire map at once
- All nodes, tensions, and emergent pattern returned in single response
- Frontend renders everything immediately
- Clicking nodes reveals summary — instant, no new AI calls
- 1 session = 620 tokens total (5x fewer than current)
- Map is coherent because AI sees the whole picture at once

### Why This Is Better For Fractal

- Stays true to README vision: “small number of clear core domains, meaningful overlaps, one synthesized grey node”
- Emergent grey node genuinely synthesizes everything
- Feels like a research field map, not a Wikipedia clone
- Groq free tier handles ~23 maps/minute comfortably

### Token Cost Analysis

- Per map: ~620 tokens (320 input + 300 output)
- Groq free tier: 14,400 tokens/minute = ~23 maps/minute free
- At 100k users doing 5 maps/day = ~$5,500/month at scale
- Completely free for prototype and early growth

### Future Architecture To Revisit (not now)

Context-aware expansion — each node click sends existing map as context so AI builds genuinely on what’s already there. Infinite AND coherent. Higher token cost but aligns with Fractal’s mission of not giving AI limited context. Revisit when product has users and token budget.

